<div class="container">

<h1>📱 Android SDK Versioning Guide</h1>

<div class="card">
<h2>1️⃣ What Are Android SDK Versions?</h2>

<p>Android applications declare three SDK values that control:</p>

<ul>
<li>Which devices can install the application</li>
<li>Which Android behavior rules the app follows</li>
<li>Which APIs are available during compilation</li>
</ul>

<table>
<tr>
<th>SDK Setting</th>
<th>Purpose</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>minSdk</td>
<td>Minimum Android version allowed to install the app</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>targetSdk</td>
<td>Android version behavior rules the app opts into</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>compileSdk</td>
<td>Android SDK used to compile the application</td>
</tr>
</table>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>2️⃣ Example Configuration</h2>

<p>A typical Android project configuration:</p>

<pre><code>android {

    compileSdk = 34

    defaultConfig {

        minSdk = 21
        targetSdk = 34

    }

}</code></pre>

<p>Meaning:</p>

<ul>
<li><code>minSdk = 21</code> → App supports Android 5.0 and newer</li>
<li><code>targetSdk = 34</code> → App follows Android 14 behavior rules</li>
<li><code>compileSdk = 34</code> → App compiled using Android 14 APIs</li>
</ul>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>3️⃣ Android Version Timeline Example</h2>

<p>Example where compileSdk and targetSdk are different.</p>

<pre><code>compileSdk = 34
targetSdk  = 30
minSdk     = 21</code></pre>

<table>
<tr>
<th>Android Version</th>
<th>SDK Level</th>
<th>Release</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 5</td>
<td>21</td>
<td>Minimum supported device</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 7</td>
<td>24</td>
<td>Older devices still supported</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 11</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>Target behavior version</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 14</td>
<td>34</td>
<td>Compilation SDK</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>This configuration means:</p>

<ul>
<li>The app installs on Android 5 and newer</li>
<li>The app behaves according to Android 11 rules</li>
<li>The code is compiled using Android 14 APIs</li>
</ul>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>4️⃣ Installation Rule</h2>

<p>Android uses a simple rule for installation.</p>

<pre><code>if device_sdk &lt; minSdk
    installation blocked

if device_sdk ≥ minSdk
    installation allowed</code></pre>

<table>
<tr>
<th>Device Android Version</th>
<th>SDK Level</th>
<th>Installation Result</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 4</td>
<td>19</td>
<td>Blocked</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 7</td>
<td>24</td>
<td>Allowed</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Android 14</td>
<td>34</td>
<td>Allowed</td>
</tr>
</table>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>5️⃣ Behavior Rule (Target SDK)</h2>

<p>Target SDK determines which Android behavior rules the app follows.</p>

<p>If the device runs a newer Android version than the target SDK, Android enables compatibility mode.</p>

<pre><code>if device_sdk &gt; targetSdk
    compatibility behavior applied</code></pre>

<table>
<tr>
<th>Device SDK</th>
<th>Target SDK</th>
<th>Result</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>24</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>Device uses native Android 7 behavior</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>31</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>Compatibility mode (Android 11 behavior)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>34</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>Compatibility mode applied</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>This prevents older apps from breaking when Android introduces stricter rules.</p>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>6️⃣ Why compileSdk Can Be Higher</h2>

<p>The compile SDK only affects compilation.</p>

<p>It does not affect runtime compatibility.</p>

<p>Example code using a newer Android API:</p>

<pre><code>if (Build.VERSION.SDK_INT >= 33) {
    requestNotificationPermission()
}</code></pre>

<p>This allows the application to safely use modern APIs while still running on older Android devices.</p>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>7️⃣ Real Production Example</h2>

<p>Many production applications use different SDK levels during migration:</p>

<pre><code>compileSdk = 34
targetSdk  = 28
minSdk     = 21</code></pre>

<table>
<tr>
<th>Purpose</th>
<th>Result</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>compileSdk = 34</td>
<td>Developers can use latest Android APIs</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>targetSdk = 28</td>
<td>App still behaves like Android 9</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>minSdk = 21</td>
<td>App supports Android 5 and newer</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>This setup is often used while updating legacy applications.</p>

</div>


<div class="card">
<h2>8️⃣ Runtime Decision Flow</h2>

<p>Android runtime behavior can be simplified into this decision flow:</p>

<pre><code>1. Check installation

if device_sdk &lt; minSdk
    block installation


2. Launch application

if device_sdk ≥ minSdk
    run application


3. Apply behavior rules

if device_sdk &gt; targetSdk
    enable compatibility behavior</code></pre>

</div>


<div class="footer">

<h2>🏆 Best Practice</h2>

<table>
<tr>
<th>Setting</th>
<th>Recommendation</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>compileSdk</td>
<td>Always use the latest stable Android SDK</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>targetSdk</td>
<td>Update regularly to comply with Google Play policies</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>minSdk</td>
<td>Choose based on the oldest device you want to support</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><strong>Modern production configuration example:</strong></p>

<pre><code>compileSdk = 34
targetSdk  = 34
minSdk     = 21</code></pre>

<p>This configuration supports most Android devices while using the latest platform APIs.</p>

</div>

